`,o.jsxs(r.p,{children:["The current implementation takes a simple approach to version management. Upgrades are deployed as ",o.jsx(r.em,{children:"new contracts"})," (at new addresses), instead of changing the contract code at the ",o.jsx(r.em,{children:"same address"}),". This is to say it operates under an expectation of ",o.jsx(r.strong,{children:"contract permanence"}),"."]}),`
`,o.jsxs(r.p,{children:["While this approach is not memory efficient (deploying a new contract for every change), the benefit is that we maintain full version history, and breaking features can be deployed without the worry of disrupting upstream contracts. This is in-line with the expected behavior of most package management systems (npm, cargo, pip, etc.)-- Sui's ",o.jsx(r.a,{href:"https://docs.sui.io/guides/developer/packages/upgrade",children:"packages are also immutable"}),"."]}),`
